Why correlations and regression models?

  • Many features of scientific interested can be measured as continuous variables
  • In medical applications, study endpoints can often be decoded as binary variables
  • Very often we are interested in relationships between two or more variables
  • Correlation methods and regression models allow us to quantify these relationships!

Correlations

What is a correlation coefficient?

  • A descriptive statistic
  • Summarises information on a sample of observations
  • Each observation has to consist of (at least) two measured features
  • Observations have to be independent of one another
  • Measurements have to be at least on an ordinal scale

A first example

  • Observations of speed and stopping distance of cars
  • Speed in mph, distance in ft (1920s cars)

Another example

  • Coma patients and their cognitive recovery (Wong et al, 2001)
  • Age at time of injury and verbal IQ score after waking up

How can we measure these relationships?

  • We want to decribe the shape of this cloud of observations in one coefficient
  • This coefficient should be independent of the scale of measurements
  • We want it to take values between 0 and 1 (plus the sign for the “direction”)

How can we measure these relationships?

  • Starting with the means of the two variables
  • We want to calculate the variation in the “y = x”-direction and compare to the total variation of both variables

Pearsons Correlation Coefficient

  • A.k.a. Product-Moment Correlation, Pearsons r, “correlation”
  • In \([-1, 1]\)
  • A measure of the strength of linear relationship between two variables

\[ r = \frac{\text{Cov}(x,y)}{\sqrt{\text{Var}(x)\text{Var}(y)}} = \frac{\sum \left ( x_{i} - \overline{x} \right ) \left ( y_{i} - \overline{y} \right )}{\sqrt{\sum \left ( x_{i} - \overline{x} \right )^{2} \sum \left ( y_{i} - \overline{y} \right )^{2}}} \]

Examples of Pearsons Correlation Coefficients

Spearmans Rank Correlation Coefficient

  • A.k.a. Rank Correlation, Spearmans Rho
  • In \([-1, 1]\)
  • A measure of the strength of any monotone relationship between two variables
  • Is equal to Pearsons Correlation calculated from the ranks of observations (smallest value = rank \(1\))
Speed (in mph) 9 10 10 10 11
Speed rank 1 3 3 3 5

Pearson versus Spearman

  • Pearson: linear - Spearman: monotone
  • Both can be used for inferential statistics
  • Pearson has more assumptions, mainly that both variables are approximately normally distributed.
  • If assumptions are met, Pearson is more powerful, i.e.better in detecting non-zero correlations

Linear Regression

Regression

main idea:

Express a response variable \(y\) as a function \(f\) of a set explanatory variables \(x:=(x_1,\ldots,x_p)\):

\[ \text{response} = f(\text{explanatory variables}) + \text{error term} \] Notation: \[ y = f(x) + \epsilon \]

  • some assumptions about \(\epsilon\): usually independent normally distributed error with mean zero
  • The type of \(f\) is assumed (e.g.: linear, polynomic, \(\ldots\))
  • But: \(f\) is unknown

Regression - Example

Suppose you want to use the NHANES data to investigate the relationship between age Age and total cholesterol Totchol

nhanes[,.(Age,TotChol)]
##         Age TotChol
##    1: 34.08    3.49

##    5: 45.08    5.82

## 2229: 20.25    4.60
## 2230: 37.42    5.15
## 2231: 43.58   13.65
## 2232: 48.92    6.36

Then

  • TotChol is the response
  • Age is the (only) explanatory variable \(x_1\)

Regression in general

main goal:

  • Find an estimate \(\widehat f\) for the the function \(f\).
  • Use \(\widehat f\) to gain insight into the relationship between \(y\) and \(x\).

two main types of applications:

  • to make predictions (forecasts) on individuals
  • to assess explained variation in the response by influential variables

Simple Linear Regression

  • simple \(\Rightarrow\) only one explanatory variable \((p=1)\)
  • linear \(\Rightarrow\) \(f\) is a linear function in \(x\)

\[ y =f(x) + \epsilon = \beta_0 + \beta_1 \cdot x + \epsilon \]

  • \(\beta_0\) is called Intercept,
  • \(\beta_1\) is the coefficient of \(x_1\).
  • But: \(\beta_0\) and \(\beta_1\) are unknown (!)

Simple Linear Regression

Aim:

To get estimates \(\widehat\beta_0,\widehat\beta_1\) for \(\beta_0,\beta_1\) from data, such that for observations \(i \in \{1,\ldots,n\}\) the fitted values \(\widehat y_i\) \[\widehat y_i = \widehat f (x_{1i})=\widehat \beta_0 + \widehat\beta_1\cdot x_{1i}\] are “close” to the real response \(y_i\).

Method:

Choose a fitting approach: Minimization of the residual sum of squares (RSS): \[ \text{RSS} := \sum_{i=1}^n \Big( y_i - \underbrace{\widehat y_i}_{= \widehat f(x_{1i})}\Big)^2 \]

Simple Linear Regression

Minimization of the RSS: \[ \widehat\beta_0,\widehat\beta_1= \underset{\tilde\beta_0,\tilde\beta_1 \in \mathbb{R}^2}{\operatorname{argmin}} \Big( \sum_{i=1}^n \big( y_i - (\tilde\beta_0 + \tilde\beta_1x_{i})\big)^2 \Big) \]

Solution \[\begin{array} \hbox{}\widehat\beta_1 &=\frac{\sum_{i=1}^n(x_i-\overline{x})(y_i-\overline{y})} {\sum_{i=1}^n (x_i-\overline{x})^2} \quad = \frac{\text{Cov}(x,y)}{\text{Var}(x)} = r_{xy}\frac{\text{sd}_y}{\text{sd}_x}\\[2ex] \widehat {\beta_0}&=\overline{y}-\widehat\beta_1 \cdot \overline x \end{array}\]


So in simple linear regression, \(\widehat\beta_1\) can be expressed with the Pearsons correlation and the sample standard deviations of \(x\) and \(y\).

Simple Linear Regression

Coefficient of determination \(R^2\)

is the proportion of variance in the response that is explained by the explanatory variable(s) \[ R^2 =1- \frac{\text{RSS}}{\text{TSS}} \] where RSS is the residual sum of squares
and TSS is the total sum of squares: \[ \text{TSS} := \sum_{i=1}^n \Big( y_i - \overline y \Big)^2 \] In simple linear regression \(R^2\) is equal to the Pearsons correlation squared: \[ R^2 = {r_{xy}}^2 \]

Simple Linear Regression

Inference in linear regression analysis


main types of hypothesis tests:

  • moments-based: t-test / z-test
  • variance-based model comparisons: F-test
  • likelihood-based model comparisons

more on that later

Multiple Linear Regression


Multiple explanatory variables \(x:=x_1,\ldots,x_p\)

\[ y = \beta_0 + \beta_1 \cdot x_1 + \ldots + \beta_p\cdot x_p + \epsilon \]

It is also possible to add a powers of the explanatory variables, e.g. \[ y = \beta_0 + \beta_1\cdot x_1 + \beta_2\cdot {x_1}^2 + \beta_3\cdot x_2 + \epsilon \] if one assumed y to be linear in \(x_2\) and quadratic in \(x_1\).

Regression - model selection

Underfitting vs overfitting


  • overfit model:
    Too specific, misinterprets some of the noise in the sample data as information
  • underfit model:
    Too general, does not manage to pick up all the information in the sample data


Balancing these two is not easy!

Regression - model selection

Model comparison

Different methods to compare models:

  • ANOVA (for nested models)
  • Comparisons of information criteria, e.g.AIC
  • Comparisons of estimated test error, cross-validation

Regression - model selection

Model comparison

These methods (especially ANOVA and AIC) are often used iteratively to select a favoured set of variables.

  • Forward selection: start with a minimal model and add the “best” variable in each step.
  • Backward selection: start with the maximal model and then drop the least informative variable in each step.

But: These ‘automated’ model selections are not flawless (!)

Example cholesterol

nullmodel <- lm(TotChol ~ 1,

Part 2

Model Evaluation


The four most important implicit assumptions are

  1. the linearity of the relation between response and explanatory variables
  2. that the residuals are approximately normally distributed
  3. that the variance of the residuals is constant (homoscedastic)
  4. that there are no highly influential individuals (outliers)


Thankfully, the plot-method in R offers visualizations to assess exactly that !

Model Evaluation

How they should look:

Model Evaluation in Linear Regression

.. and now how they should not ..

Model Evaluation in Linear Regression

1. Non-linear relationship

  • Try transformations: e.g.\(\tilde x := x^2\)
  • Are important explanatory variables missing?

Model Evaluation in Linear Regression

2. Non-normal residuals

  • Try transformations of the response: e.g.\(\tilde y := \text{log} (y)\)
  • Are there clusters in the data structure?

Model Evaluation in Linear Regression

3. Non-constant residual variance (Heteroscedasicity)

  • Try transformation: e.g.\(\tilde x := \text{log} (x)\)
  • use heteroscedasticity-consistent estimators for inference (e.g.lmtest::coeftest())

Model Evaluation in Linear Regression

4. Highly Influential Individuals (Outliers)

  • Check the individual observation (here 51) carefully for data errors.
  • Redefine inclusion criteria to exclude that observation or apply weights to lessen its effect

Linear Regression

Inference in linear regression analysis: t-test

In linear regression, closed formulae for the standard errors of the regression coefficients can be derived.
In a simple linear model, the standard error of \(\widehat\beta_1\) is: \[ \text{se}_{\widehat\beta_1} = \sqrt{\frac{\frac{1}{n-2}\sum_{i=1}^n {\widehat\epsilon_i}^2} {\sum_{i=1}^n (x_i-\overline x)^2}} \]

This enables us to conduct a t-test with \(n-2\) degrees of freedom \[ t=\frac{\widehat\beta_1 - \beta_1}{\text{se}_{\widehat\beta_1}} \sim t_{n-2} \]

Linear Regression

Inference in linear regression analysis: t-test

This is what summary() presents. Recap example cholesterol:

##               Estimate  Std. Error  t value      Pr(>|t|)
## (Intercept) 3.78116611 0.081766302 46.24357 1.976263e-323
## Age         0.03523166 0.002288214 15.39701  8.607269e-51

Now calculate the standard error manually:

n       <- dim ( nhanes ) [1]   
sq_res  <- sum( (lm1$residuals)^2 ) / (n-2) ## sum of squared residuals
se_b1   <- sqrt( sq_res / (var(lm1$model$Age)*(n-1)) )  
se_b0   <- se_b1*sqrt(mean(lm1$model$Age^2)) 

print( c( se_b0 , se_b1 ))
## [1] 0.07780721 0.00217742

Linear Regression

Inference in linear regression analysis: F-test

tests whether the explained variance in the population is greater than zero.

Cohens \(f^2\):

\[ f^2 = \frac{R^2}{1-R^2} \qquad = \frac{\text{"explained variance"}}{\text{"unexplained variance"}} \]

This \(f^2\) is \(F\)-distributed \[ f^2 \sim F_{u,v} \]

  • numerator df \(u\) = number of variables in the model +1 \((u=p+1)\)
  • denominator df \(v\) = number of observations \(n\) minus numerator degrees of freedom \((v=n-u=n-p-1)\)

Linear Regression

Inference in linear regression analysis: F-test


If one wants to test whether a second set of variables \(B\) has additional explanatory power beyond a first set of variables \(A\), then \(f^2\) becomes: \[ f^2 = \frac{R_{AB}^2 - R_A^2}{1 - R_{AB}^2} \sim F_{u,v} \] where

  • \(u\) equals the number of variables in the second set \(u=p_B\) and
  • \(v=n- (p_A + p_B+1)\)

Sample Size Calculation

example A

The attitude of patients towards a new treatment \(att\) is investigated. A small pilot study suggests that age is (negatively) correlated with the response attitude; the \(R^2\) of a simple linear regression is \(R^2_{age}=0.1\).

To investigate the alternative hypothesis with an F-Test, that \(age\) contributes to \(att\) in the population, with significance level \(\alpha=0.05\) and power set to 90%, how many persons need to be asked?

Sample Size Calculation

example A: \(u=1\), \(R^2=0.1\), \(\alpha=0.05\), \(power=0.9\)

f2 <- (0.1)/(1-0.1)               ## calculate f^2
pwr.f2.test(u=1,f2=f2,power=0.9)  ## F-test
## 
##      Multiple regression power calculation 
## 
##               u = 1
##               v = 94.52855
##              f2 = 0.1111111
##       sig.level = 0.05
##           power = 0.9
  • The needed sample size is \(\lceil v \rceil +2=97\)

Sample Size Calculation

example B

The effect of education is also suspected to have an influence on the patients attitude. But since education and age are correlated, the aim is to obtain the effect of education only (i.e.the effect of education adjusted for age).

In the pilot data: \(R^2_{age,education}=0.15\) and \(R^2_{age}=0.12.\) Power is set to 90%, \(\alpha=0.05\).

Sample Size Calculation

example B: \(u=1\), \(R^2_{A}=0.1\), \(R^2_{AB}=0.17\), \(\alpha=0.05\), \(power=0.9\)

f2 <- (0.15 - 0.1)/(1 - 0.15)
pwr.f2.test(u=1,f2=f2,power=0.9)
## 
##      Multiple regression power calculation 
## 
##               u = 1
##               v = 178.5686
##              f2 = 0.05882353
##       sig.level = 0.05
##           power = 0.9
  • The needed sample size is \(\lceil v \rceil +2 + 1 = 182\)

  • for regression models more complicated than linear regressions, the output of the plot function is almost not interpretable.
  • simulate from the model many residuals for each observation
  • compare the actual residual with the simulated residuals.

Caveats

  • dont get confused with the names:
    • response a.k.a. regressand a.k.a. dependent variable
    • expanatory variables a.k.a. regressors a.k.a. independent variables
  • avoid high multicolliniarity in the explanatory variables
